WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:04.290
We learned in the last video
that if I have some matrix--

00:00:04.290 --> 00:00:10.490
let's call it C, Let's say
it's an n by k matrix.

00:00:10.490 --> 00:00:13.790
And all of matrix C's columns--
let's say this is

00:00:13.790 --> 00:00:19.500
column 1, column 2, all the way
through column k-- if each

00:00:19.500 --> 00:00:23.955
of these columns vectors form
an orthonormal set-- so, let

00:00:23.955 --> 00:00:28.850
me write this-- columns are
orthonormal set, or the set of

00:00:28.850 --> 00:00:34.210
columns are an orthonormal set,
we showed in the last

00:00:34.210 --> 00:00:40.040
video that if I multiply C
transpose times C, I get the

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:41.090
identity matrix.

00:00:41.090 --> 00:00:44.440
I get the k by k identity
matrix.

00:00:44.440 --> 00:00:46.870
I get the identity matrix of k,
because it's going to be k

00:00:46.870 --> 00:00:49.250
by n, times n by k.

00:00:49.250 --> 00:00:51.920
And we saw how everything else
cancels out, except right

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:52.380
along the diagonal.

00:00:52.380 --> 00:00:54.840
And then we were just
multiplying the vectors times

00:00:54.840 --> 00:00:57.040
themselves, and they're
all unit vectors.

00:00:57.040 --> 00:00:59.680
So you get the square of their
lengths and you get 1's down

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:00.150
the diagonal.

00:01:00.150 --> 00:01:01.830
We saw that in the last video.

00:01:01.830 --> 00:01:06.840
Now what happens if
k is equal to n?

00:01:06.840 --> 00:01:09.980
So what happens if
k is equal to n?

00:01:09.980 --> 00:01:12.345
Well, then this guy is going
to be a square matrix.

00:01:17.635 --> 00:01:19.950
And if he's a square matrix,
what else do we know about it?

00:01:19.950 --> 00:01:23.470
Well, we know that these guys
form an orthonormal set.

00:01:23.470 --> 00:01:25.750
We saw, I think it was two or
three videos ago, that that

00:01:25.750 --> 00:01:27.910
means that the columns are
linearly independent.

00:01:27.910 --> 00:01:32.420
So we also know that we have
linearly independent columns.

00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:34.880
And we've seen this many,
many times before.

00:01:34.880 --> 00:01:37.370
If we have a square matrix
with linearly independent

00:01:37.370 --> 00:01:40.000
columns, it means that
C is invertible.

00:01:45.030 --> 00:01:48.450
It also means, if we have n of
these, it also means that

00:01:48.450 --> 00:01:52.570
these columns, or these column
vectors, if they were in a

00:01:52.570 --> 00:01:55.650
set, then that set would
be a basis for Rn.

00:01:55.650 --> 00:01:57.590
So I'll just write that on the
side, just because it, you

00:01:57.590 --> 00:02:02.950
know, it also would mean that,
you know, c1, c2, all the way

00:02:02.950 --> 00:02:07.210
through cn, because we're saying
n is equal to k, would

00:02:07.210 --> 00:02:12.540
be a basis for Rn.

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:14.200
But we'll leave that on
the side for now.

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:15.950
It's just worth pointing out.

00:02:15.950 --> 00:02:18.230
Now if C is invertible,
what does that mean?

00:02:18.230 --> 00:02:22.180
That means that there's some C
inverse that exists, such that

00:02:22.180 --> 00:02:27.840
C inverse times C is equal to
the n by n identity matrix.

00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:30.210
In this case k and n are equal
to the same thing, so let's

00:02:30.210 --> 00:02:32.990
just replace that n,
that k with an n.

00:02:32.990 --> 00:02:35.350
Now these two statements
look very similar.

00:02:35.350 --> 00:02:38.850
If the columns are an
orthonormal set, and it's an n

00:02:38.850 --> 00:02:42.940
by n matrix, then we learned
in the last video that C

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:47.700
transpose times C is equal to
the n by n identity matrix.

00:02:47.700 --> 00:02:50.350
And we also know, since it's a
square matrix with linearly

00:02:50.350 --> 00:02:53.050
independent columns, that
C is invertible.

00:02:53.050 --> 00:03:01.140
So, in this situation where you
have n by n matrix whose

00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:16.260
columns form an orthonormal
set, then, well, C inverse

00:03:16.260 --> 00:03:18.290
must be equal to C transpose.

00:03:18.290 --> 00:03:21.275
I mean, you can just say, look,
something times C is

00:03:21.275 --> 00:03:21.920
equal to the identity matrix.

00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:23.380
Something times C is the
identity matrix.

00:03:23.380 --> 00:03:26.190
These somethings must
be the same thing.

00:03:26.190 --> 00:03:30.800
Then C inverse is equal
to C transpose.

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:32.910
And that is a huge time saver.

00:03:32.910 --> 00:03:35.230
If we can assume that these,
this is a square matrix with

00:03:35.230 --> 00:03:36.510
an orthonormal set.

00:03:36.510 --> 00:03:39.130
Because finding an inverse
of a matrix is painful,

00:03:39.130 --> 00:03:41.870
especially if you get,
you know, beyond, you

00:03:41.870 --> 00:03:43.100
know, n equals 3.

00:03:43.100 --> 00:03:45.280
If you have to find the inverse
of a, I don't know, 10

00:03:45.280 --> 00:03:47.130
by 10 matrix, that would
take you forever.

00:03:47.130 --> 00:03:50.120
But to find the transpose of a
10 by 10 matrix, a lot easier.

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:52.920
You just swap the rows
and the columns.

00:03:52.920 --> 00:03:57.960
So let's see if we can apply
