x-- sorry, by some matrix A--

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:53.260
to get your transformation
of x.

00:08:53.260 --> 00:08:55.480
Now, we're saying that this is
hard to find, because it's

00:08:55.480 --> 00:08:57.560
hard to figure out what the
transformation is when you

00:08:57.560 --> 00:09:01.350
apply to just your standard
basis vectors.

00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:04.900
So what I'm going to do is try
to construct some basis, so

00:09:04.900 --> 00:09:11.080
that when I represent x in that
new basis, if I multiply

00:09:11.080 --> 00:09:15.440
x times the inverse of our
change of basis matrix, then

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:19.840
I'm going to get x in the
new basis coordinates.

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:24.360
And maybe it'll be easier to
find the D in this new basis,

00:09:24.360 --> 00:09:28.980
and then we'll get the B
representation of the

00:09:28.980 --> 00:09:30.950
transformation of x.

00:09:30.950 --> 00:09:34.900
And then we can multiply
that times C.

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:38.310
So if we're able to figure out
D, what we can do is, look, we

00:09:38.310 --> 00:09:45.150
know that the transformation
of x is going to be

00:09:45.150 --> 00:09:47.710
able to A times x.

00:09:47.710 --> 00:09:50.690
We saw that a long time ago,
that any linear transformation

00:09:50.690 --> 00:09:53.330
could be represented as a
matrix vector product.

00:09:53.330 --> 00:09:55.450
But let's say that this
is hard to find.

00:09:55.450 --> 00:09:56.430
This is hard.

00:09:56.430 --> 00:09:59.120
Then we can go the other
way around this.

00:09:59.120 --> 00:10:06.160
We could say that the
transformation of x is equal

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:10.720
to you take x, first you
multiply it by C inverse to

00:10:10.720 --> 00:10:12.780
get the B version of x.

00:10:12.780 --> 00:10:14.990
So first you multiply
it by C inverse.

00:10:14.990 --> 00:10:18.660
Then you multiply it by D, to
get the B version of the

00:10:18.660 --> 00:10:20.360
transformation of x.

00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:22.320
So then you multiply it by D.

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:25.390
And then you multiply that by
C to go back to our standard

00:10:25.390 --> 00:10:26.780
basis for the transformation.

00:10:26.780 --> 00:10:28.630
So then you go multiply
it by C.

00:10:28.630 --> 00:10:30.430
And we've seen this
formula before.

00:10:30.430 --> 00:10:33.910
So if we can find a nice basis
where D is easy to figure out,

00:10:33.910 --> 00:10:37.700
then we can multiply it this
way, times the change in basis

00:10:37.700 --> 00:10:41.920
matrix and its inverse,
and we'll get our A.

00:10:41.920 --> 00:10:45.510
Because this thing has to be the
same thing as that thing

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:46.320
right there.

00:10:46.320 --> 00:10:53.510
And even more, if we pick an
orthonormal basis, if B is an

00:10:53.510 --> 00:11:05.350
orthonormal basis, with three
vectors, right, then C will be

00:11:05.350 --> 00:11:06.090
invertible.

00:11:06.090 --> 00:11:08.635
Well, we already know if it's an
orthonormal basis, we know

00:11:08.635 --> 00:11:16.710
that C transpose C is equal
to the identity matrix.

00:11:16.710 --> 00:11:21.060
And we also know that C is
invertible, if, you know, C is

00:11:21.060 --> 00:11:23.220
essentially a 3 by 3 matrix.

00:11:23.220 --> 00:11:24.940
C inverse exists.

00:11:24.940 --> 00:11:26.870
And in the beginning of this
video, we said, well that

00:11:26.870 --> 00:11:29.210
means that C transpose is
going to be equal to C

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:30.940
Inverse, because this is
just acting like an

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:32.180
inverse right there.

00:11:32.180 --> 00:11:37.950
And then, if C is an n by n
matrix, or in this case we're

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:41.810
dealing with a 3 by 3 matrix,
we're dealing with R3, then it

00:11:41.810 --> 00:11:47.580
simplifies to A will be equal
to C times D, times the C

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:51.170
transpose, which is much easier
to find, much easier to

00:11:51.170 --> 00:11:53.920
find than trying to invert
a 3 by 3 matrix.

00:11:53.920 --> 00:11:56.560
So let's see if we can
do this effectively.

00:11:56.560 --> 00:11:58.290
So what would be a good basis?

00:11:58.290 --> 00:12:00.810
Well I think maybe a natural
one would be to use v1, v2,

00:12:00.810 --> 00:12:03.910
and v3, because these basis
vectors, it's very easy to

00:12:03.910 --> 00:12:07.040
figure out what their
