equal to 1, 0, 0.

00:12:49.880 --> 00:12:50.750
Same argument.

00:12:50.750 --> 00:12:54.090
v2, what is it going to be
equal to in my new basis?

00:12:54.090 --> 00:12:56.180
I don't even have to, I think
you get the idea.

00:12:56.180 --> 00:12:57.770
Let me just write
it over here.

00:12:57.770 --> 00:13:04.220
v2 in my new basis is just
going to be 0 times v1--

00:13:04.220 --> 00:13:06.770
remember, these numbers, these
coordinates are just the

00:13:06.770 --> 00:13:09.240
coefficients on my basis
vectors-- it's going to be 0

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:16.210
times v1, plus 1 times
v2, plus 0, times v3.

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:24.690
And then finally, v3 in my new
basis is just going to be 0

00:13:24.690 --> 00:13:30.080
times v1, plus 0 times v2,
plus 1 times v3, This is

